 to Settings in Windows 11.\n                        \u003c/li\u003e\n                    \u003cli\u003e\n                                        Recent changes include language settings, which are hidden in Dev and Beta builds.\n                        \u003c/li\u003e\n                    \u003cli\u003e\n                                        The hidden feature suggests Microsoft is working out bugs before wider release.\n                        \u003c/li\u003e\n            \u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n    \n        \n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOver the past few months, we\u0026#39;ve seen Microsoft drag its heels over scrapping the Control Panel. I mean, we \u003cem\u003eknow\u003c/em\u003e it wants to make the swap over to Settings already, but it\u0026#39;s just seemingly taking its sweet time about it. We\u0026#39;ve seen the company move a handful of tools, then seemingly go to sleep, then move a few more after a hiatus, and then go back into hibernation.\u003c/p\u003e    \n\u003cp\u003eHowever, that may have changed. We \u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/microsoft-dismantle-control-panel/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003elast saw Microsoft move something around two weeks ago\u003c/a\u003e, but the company is already planning to migrate more features over. As such, if you\u0026#39;re a fan of the Control Panel, now may be a good time to say your goodbyes.\u003c/p\u003e            \n    \n                    \n                        \n    \n    \n                                        \n    \n        \n    \n        \n                \n        \n    \u003cdiv data-include-community-rating=\"false\" id=\"576d-46a6-90b275e48b8f\" data-nosnippet=\"\"\u003e\n        \n        \n                        \t                \n\t\t\u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/windows-11-patch-tuesday-may/\"\u003e\n\t\n\t\u003cdiv data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/windows-11-robotask-and-power-automate-1.